{"title_page": "Patrick Nip", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Patrick Nip Tak-kuen\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-hk\n| honorific-suffix = [[Justice of the Peace|JP]]\n| image            =  File:\u9999\u6e2f\u653f\u5236\u53ca\u5167\u5730\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40\u5c40\u9577\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a (cropped).jpg\n| caption          =  \n| office           = [[Secretary for the Civil Service]]\n| term_start       = 22 April 2020 \n| term_end         = \n| 1blankname  = Chief Executive\n| 1namedata  = [[Carrie Lam]]\n| predecessor      = [[Joshua Law]]\n| successor        = \n| office1          = [[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]]\n| term_start1      = 1 July 2017\n| term_end1        = 22 April 2020\n| 1blankname1 = Chief Executive\n| 1namedata1 = [[Carrie Lam]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Raymond Tam]]\n| successor1       = [[Erick Tsang]]\n| office2          = Permanent Secretary for Food and Health (Health)\n| term_start2      = 2016\n| term_end2        = 30 June 2016\n| 1blankname2 = Secretary for Food and Health\n| 1namedata2 = [[Ko Wing-man]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Richard Yuen]]\n| successor2       = [[Elizabeth Tse]]\n| office3          = Director of Information Services\n| term_start3      = 2014\n| term_end3        = 2016\n| predecessor3     = [[Michael Wong Wai-lun|Michael Wong]]\n| successor3       = [[Joe Wong (civil servant)|Joe Wong]]\n| office4          = Director of Social Welfare\n| term_start4      = 2009\n| term_end4        = 2013\n| predecessor4     = [[Stephen Fredrick Fisher]]\n| successor4       = [[Carol Yip]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1964}}\n| birth_place      = \n| birthname        = \n| nationality      = \n| party            = \n| spouse           = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Hong Kong]]<br>[[Harvard Kennedy School]]\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Nip Tak-kuen''' ({{zh-t|\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a}}; born 1964) is a Hong Kong government official. Since April 2020, he has been [[Secretary for the Civil Service]] in [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Carrie Lam]]'s administration.\n\n==Background==\nNip attended [[Kwun Tong Maryknoll College]] and then the [[University of Hong Kong]], graduating in 1986. He obtained a master's degree in public administration from [[Harvard Kennedy School]] and has also studied at [[Oxford University]] and attended national studies courses at the Chinese Academy of Governance.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mr Patrick Nip Tak-kuen, JP, Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs|url=https://www.gov.hk/en/about/govdirectory/po/scma.htm|work=Hong Kong government}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNip joined the Administrative Service in August 1986, serving in various bureaux and departments, including the [[Home Affairs Bureau|City and New Territories Administration]], the [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Deputy Chief Secretary's Office]], the [[Trade and Industry Department|Trade and Industry Branch]], the Finance Branch, the Civil Service Branch, the Trade Department, the [[Chief Executive's Office]], the former Health and Welfare Bureau, the Beijing Office and the former Health, Welfare and Food Bureau.<ref name=\"gov\"/>\n\nHe was appointed [[Social Welfare Department|Director of Social Welfare]] in 2009 and Director (Special Duties) in the Chief Secretary for Administration's Private Office in 2013, before becoming Director of [[Information Services Department|Information Services]] in February 2014. For a year from July 2016 he was Permanent Secretary for [[Department of Health (Hong Kong)|Food and Health (Health)]].<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite news|title=Senior appointments (with photos)|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201606/28/P201606280342.htm}}</ref>\n\nFrom July 2017, Nip was [[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]]. But in a cabinet reshuffle on 22 April 2020, Lam removed him from the role (to be replaced by [[Erick Tsang]]). The announcement came two days after Nip's office had issued (and then amended) press statements that failed to reflect [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|Beijing]]'s assertion that the [[Hong Kong Liaison Office|Liaison Office]] and [[Hong Kong and Macau Affairs Office]] were not subject to Article 22 of the [[Hong Kong Basic Law|Basic Law]], preventing interference in Hong Kong affairs by mainland authorities. Until then, all branches of the Hong Kong Government had always stated that they were, and indeed it was widely held that that such effect was central to the '[[one country, two systems]] principle.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/21/just-in-mainland-affairs-minister-patrick-nip-replaced-following-apology-over-beijing-office-row/ |title= Mainland affairs minister Patrick Nip replaced following apology over Beijing office row |last= Ho |first= Kelly |date= 2020-04-21 |website= Hong Kong Free Press |publisher= HKFP |access-date= 2020-04-21|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3080822/top-hong-kong-official-loses-job-cabinet-reshuffle-amid |title=Hong Kong leader Carrie Lam to announce major cabinet reshuffle with four ministers leaving and another transferred, sources reveal |last=Cheung |first=Gary |date=2020-04-21 |website= |publisher=SCMP |access-date=2020-04-21 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nNip immediately took up the role of [[Secretary for the Civil Service]], controversially the first non-civil servant to hold the post, at a time of emerging political activism within Civil Service ranks and pressure from Beijing for unswerving loyalty from all Hong Kong government staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3081132/new-civil-service-chief-faces-daunting-challenge-pleasing |title=Hong Kong\u2019s new civil service chief faces daunting challenge of pleasing Beijing while boosting staff morale, experts say |last=Cheng |first=Lillian|date=2020-04-23 |website= |publisher=SCMP |access-date=2020-04-23 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Frederick Fisher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of Social Welfare |years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Carol Yip]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Wong Wai-lun|Michael Wong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of Information Services |years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joe Wong Chi-cho|Joe Wong]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard Yuen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Permanent Secretary for [[Food and Health Bureau|Food and Health]] (Health)|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Elizabeth Tse]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raymond Tam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]] |years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Erick Tsang]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joshua Law]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary for the Civil Service]] |years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{HKExco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nip, Patrick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Government officials of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong civil servants]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name             = Patrick Nip Tak-kuen\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-hk\n| honorific-suffix = [[Justice of the Peace|JP]]\n| image            =  File:\u9999\u6e2f\u653f\u5236\u53ca\u5167\u5730\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40\u5c40\u9577\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a (cropped).jpg\n| caption          =  \n| office           = [[Secretary for the Civil Service]]\n| term_start       = 22 April 2020 \n| term_end         = \n| 1blankname  = Chief Executive\n| 1namedata  = [[Carrie Lam]]\n| predecessor      = [[Joshua Law]]\n| successor        = \n| office1          = [[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]]\n| term_start1      = 1 July 2017\n| term_end1        = 22 April 2020\n| 1blankname1 = Chief Executive\n| 1namedata1 = [[Carrie Lam]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Raymond Tam]]\n| successor1       = [[Erick Tsang]]\n| office2          = Permanent Secretary for Food and Health (Health)\n| term_start2      = 2016\n| term_end2        = 30 June 2016\n| 1blankname2 = Secretary for Food and Health\n| 1namedata2 = [[Ko Wing-man]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Richard Yuen]]\n| successor2       = [[Elizabeth Tse]]\n| office3          = Director of Information Services\n| term_start3      = 2014\n| term_end3        = 2016\n| predecessor3     = [[Michael Wong Wai-lun|Michael Wong]]\n| successor3       = [[Joe Wong (civil servant)|Joe Wong]]\n| office4          = Director of Social Welfare\n| term_start4      = 2009\n| term_end4        = 2013\n| predecessor4     = [[Stephen Fredrick Fisher]]\n| successor4       = [[Carol Yip]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1964}}\n| birth_place      = \n| birthname        = \n| nationality      = \n| party            = \n| spouse           = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Hong Kong]]<br>[[Harvard Kennedy School]]\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Nip Tak-kuen''' ({{zh-t|\u8076\u5fb7\u6b0a}}; born 1964) is a Hong Kong government official. Since April 2020, he has been [[Secretary for the Civil Service]] in [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Carrie Lam]]'s administration.\n\n==Background==\nNip attended [[Kwun Tong Maryknoll College]] and then the [[University of Hong Kong]], graduating in 1986. He obtained a master's degree in public administration from [[Harvard Kennedy School]] and has also studied at [[Oxford University]] and attended national studies courses at the Chinese Academy of Governance.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mr Patrick Nip Tak-kuen, JP, Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs|url=https://www.gov.hk/en/about/govdirectory/po/scma.htm|work=Hong Kong government}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNip joined the Administrative Service in August 1986, serving in various bureaux and departments, including the [[Home Affairs Bureau|City and New Territories Administration]], the [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Deputy Chief Secretary's Office]], the [[Trade and Industry Department|Trade and Industry Branch]], the Finance Branch, the Civil Service Branch, the Trade Department, the [[Chief Executive's Office]], the former Health and Welfare Bureau, the Beijing Office and the former Health, Welfare and Food Bureau.<ref name=\"gov\"/>\n\nHe was appointed [[Social Welfare Department|Director of Social Welfare]] in 2009 and Director (Special Duties) in the Chief Secretary for Administration's Private Office in 2013, before becoming Director of [[Information Services Department|Information Services]] in February 2014. For a year from July 2016 he was Permanent Secretary for [[Department of Health (Hong Kong)|Food and Health (Health)]].<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite news|title=Senior appointments (with photos)|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201606/28/P201606280342.htm}}</ref>\n\nFrom July 2017, Nip was [[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]]. But in a cabinet reshuffle on 22 April 2020, Lam removed him from the role (to be replaced by [[Erick Tsang]]). The announcement came two days after Nip's office had issued (and then amended) press statements that failed to reflect [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|Beijing]]'s assertion that the [[Hong Kong Liaison Office|Liaison Office]] and [[Hong Kong and Macau Affairs Office]] were not subject to Article 22 of the [[Hong Kong Basic Law|Basic Law]], preventing interference in Hong Kong affairs by mainland authorities. Until then, all branches of the Hong Kong Government had always stated that they were, and indeed it was widely held that that such effect was central to the '[[one country, two systems]] principle.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/21/just-in-mainland-affairs-minister-patrick-nip-replaced-following-apology-over-beijing-office-row/ |title= Mainland affairs minister Patrick Nip replaced following apology over Beijing office row |last= Ho |first= Kelly |date= 2020-04-21 |website= Hong Kong Free Press |publisher= HKFP |access-date= 2020-04-21|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3080822/top-hong-kong-official-loses-job-cabinet-reshuffle-amid |title=Hong Kong leader Carrie Lam to announce major cabinet reshuffle with four ministers leaving and another transferred, sources reveal |last=Cheung |first=Gary |date=2020-04-21 |website= |publisher=SCMP |access-date=2020-04-21 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nNip immediately took up the role of [[Secretary for the Civil Service]], controversially the first non-civil servant to hold the post, at at time of emerging political activism within Civil Service ranks and pressure from Beijing for unswerving loyalty from all Hong Kong government staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/3081132/new-civil-service-chief-faces-daunting-challenge-pleasing |title=Hong Kong\u2019s new civil service chief faces daunting challenge of pleasing Beijing while boosting staff morale, experts say |last=Cheng |first=Lillian|date=2020-04-23 |website= |publisher=SCMP |access-date=2020-04-23 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Frederick Fisher]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of Social Welfare |years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Carol Yip]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Wong Wai-lun|Michael Wong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of Information Services |years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joe Wong Chi-cho|Joe Wong]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard Yuen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Permanent Secretary for [[Food and Health Bureau|Food and Health]] (Health)|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Elizabeth Tse]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raymond Tam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary for Constitutional and Mainland Affairs]] |years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Erick Tsang]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joshua Law]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary for the Civil Service]] |years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{HKExco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nip, Patrick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Government officials of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong civil servants]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Nip"}
{"title_page": "Little Women (2018 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Little Women\n| image          = Little Women 2018 poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Clare Niederpruem\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Maclain Nelson\n* Kristi Shimek\n* Stephen Shimek\n* David M. Wulf\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Clare Niederpruem\n* Kristi Shimek\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Little Women]]||[[Louisa May Alcott]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Sarah Davenport\n* Allie Jennings\n* [[Lucas Grabeel]]\n* [[Ian Bohen]]\n* [[Lea Thompson]]\n}}\n| music          = Robert Allen Elliott\n| cinematography = Anka Malatynska\n| editing        = Kristi Shimek\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Main Dog Productions\n* [[Paulist Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pure Flix Entertainment]]\n* Pinnacle Peak\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|28|United States}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $1.4\u00a0million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Little Women (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=littlewomen2018.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Little Women''''' is a 2018 American [[drama film|drama]] film directed by Clare Niederpruem, from a screenplay by Niederpruem and Kristi Shimek. The sixth film adaptation of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s [[Little Women|1868 novel of the same name]], it is a modern retelling of the original story and marks the 150th anniversary of the book's release. The film stars Sarah Davenport, Allie Jennings, [[Lucas Grabeel]], [[Ian Bohen]], and [[Lea Thompson]]. It was released in the United States on September 28, 2018, by Pinnacle Peak.\n\n==Cast==\n* Sarah Davenport as Jo March\n**Aimee Lynne Johnson as Young Jo\n* Allie Jennings as Beth March\n**Reese Oliveira as Young Beth\n* Melanie Stone as Meg March\n* Taylor Murphy as Amy March\n**Elise Jones as Young Amy\n* [[Lucas Grabeel]] as Theodore \"Laurie\" Laurence \n* [[Stuart Edge]] as John Brooke\n* [[Ian Bohen]] as Frederick \"Freddy\" Bhaer\n* [[Lea Thompson]] as Marmee March\n* [[Bart Johnson]] as Papa March\n* Adam Johnson as Duke Senior\n* Michael Flynn as Mr. Laurence\n\n==Production==\nIn April 2017, it was announced [[Lea Thompson]] and [[Lucas Grabeel]] had joined the cast of the film, with Clare Niederpruem directing from a screenplay she wrote alongside Kristi Shimek, based upon the novel of the same name by [[Louisa May Alcott]].  Maclain Nelson and Stephen Shimek will serve as producers on the film, while Chris Donahue and Marybeth Sprows, will executive produce the film under their Main Dog Productions and Paulist Productions banners, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/lea-thompson-adaptation-little-women-movie-1202078635/|title=Lea Thompson To Star In New Feature Adaptation Of \u2018Little Women\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, Sarah Davenport and [[Ian Bohen]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/ryan-hansen-bum-deal-ian-bohen-little-women-1202107757/|title=Ryan Hansen To Co-Star In \u2018Bum Deal\u2019; Ian Bohen Joins \u2018Little Women\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=June 8, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] began in June 2017, in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/artsliving/2017/04/30/modern-take-on-little-women-to-be-filmed-in-utah/|title=Modern take on \u2018Little Women\u2019 to be filmed in Utah|website=[[The Salt Lake City Tribune]]|first=Sean|last=P. Means|date=April 30, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn June 2018, it was announced Pinnacle Peak and [[Pure Flix Entertainment]] would distribute the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pinnacle-peak-to-release-modern-retelling-of-timeless-family-story-little-women-in-theaters-sept-28-300666702.html|title=Pinnacle Peak to Release Modern Retelling of Timeless Family Story \"Little Women\" In Theaters Sept. 28|website=PR Newswire|date=June 14, 2018|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> It was released in the United States on September 28, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/reelfaith/2018/06/trailer-first-look-at-modern-retelling-of-little-women-starring-lea-thompson.html|title=TRAILER: First Look at Modern Retelling of \u2018Little Women\u2019 Starring Lea Thompson|website=Patheos|first=Dewayne|last=Hamby|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Little Women'' was released alongside ''[[Smallfoot (film)|Smallfoot]]'', ''[[Night School (2018 film)|Night School]]'' and ''[[Hell Fest]]'', and was projected to gross $3\u20135 million from 643 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/night-school-box-office-debut-kevin-hart-tiffany-haddish-1202931274/|title=Kevin Hart-Tiffany Haddish\u2019s \u2018Night School\u2019 to Score High Marks in Box Office Debut|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=September 9, 2018|accessdate=September 25, 2018}}</ref> It ended up grossing just $747,000, finishing 16th at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/night-school-tiffany-haddish-kevin-hart-weekend-box-office-1202472883/|title=\u2018Night School\u2019 Top Of The Weekend\u2019s Box Office Class With $28M; Best Opening For A Comedy So Far This Year|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=September 30, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nAccording to the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], 27% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 26 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 4.81/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"This updated version of ''Little Women'' may hold some appeal for newcomers, but fans of the classic source material have far better adaptations to choose from.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/little_women_2018 |title=Little Women (2018) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 40 out of 100 based on 11 critic reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/little-women-2018 |title=Little Women (2018) Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref> Nell Minow of RogerEbert.com gave it 3 out of 4 stars and wrote, \"For devotees, the essence of the Little Women story remains, and, for newcomers, it is a sweet film that should inspire them to explore the book and the more traditional adaptations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/little-women-2018|title=Little Women Movie Review & Film Summary (2018) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Minow|first=Nell|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> But Elizabeth Weitzman of The Wrap gave it low marks, writing, \"The girls in this contemporary retelling ... are not messy and complex human beings but Hallmark Channel characters, two-dimensional symbols of virtuous nostalgia.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/little-women-film-review-2018-lea-thompson/|title='Little Women' Film Review: Contemporary Take on Literary Classic Feels More Old-Fashioned Than the Original|date=2018-09-27|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Faith-based reviewers were more generous. Kristin Smith of Plugged In said the film \"illustrates the importance of loving one another, of practicing forgiveness and of moving forward despite difficult times.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pluggedin.com/|title=Plugged In|website=Plugged In|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Michael Foust of Crosswalk wrote that \"unlike other modern-day film adaptations that spoiled a classic, Little Women is an updated version that doesn\u2019t ruin what made the original great. ...  Here\u2019s hoping [Niederpruem] makes many more like this one.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crosswalk.com/culture/features/5-reasons-you-should-watch-the-newest-little-women.html|title=5 Reasons You Should Watch the Newest Little Women|website=Crosswalk.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB title|6495094}}\n\n{{Little Women}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about sisters]]\n[[Category:Little Women films]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Little Women\n| image          = Little Women 2018 poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Clare Niederpruem\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Maclain Nelson\n* Kristi Shimek\n* Stephen Shimek\n* David M. Wulf\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Clare Niederpruem\n* Kristi Shimek\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Little Women]]||[[Louisa May Alcott]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Sarah Davenport\n* Allie Jennings\n* [[Lucas Grabeel]]\n* [[Ian Bohen]]\n* [[Lea Thompson]]\n}}\n| music          = Robert Allen Elliott\n| cinematography = Anka Malatynska\n| editing        = Kristi Shimek\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Main Dog Productions\n* [[Paulist Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pure Flix Entertainment]]\n* Pinnacle Peak\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|9|28|United States}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $1.4\u00a0million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |title=Little Women (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=littlewomen2018.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Little Women''''' is a 2018 American [[drama film|drama]] film directed by Clare Niederpruem, from a screenplay by Niederpruem and Kristi Shimek. The sixth film adaptation of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s [[Little Women|1868 novel of the same name]], it is a modern retelling of the original story and marks the 150th anniversary of the book's release. The film stars Sarah Davenport, Allie Jennings, [[Lucas Grabeel]], [[Ian Bohen]], and [[Lea Thompson]]. It was released in the United States on September 28, 2018, by Pinnacle Peak.\n\n==Cast==\n* Sarah Davenport as Jo March\n**Aimee Lynne Johnson as Young Jo\n* Allie Jennings as Beth March\n**Reese Oliveira as Young Beth\n* Melanie Stone as Meg March\n* Taylor Murphy as Amy March\n**Elise Jones as Young Amy\n* [[Lucas Grabeel]] as Theodore \"Laurie\" Laurence \n* [[Stuart Edge]] as John Brooke\n* [[Ian Bohen]] as Frederick \"Freddy\" Bhaer\n* [[Lea Thompson]] as Marmee March\n* [[Bart Johnson]] as Papa March\n* Adam Johnson as Duke Senior\n* Michael Flynn as Mr. Laurence\n\n==Production==\nIn April 2017, it was announced [[Lea Thompson]] and [[Lucas Grabeel]] had joined the cast of the film, with Clare Niederpruem directing from a screenplay she wrote alongside Kristi Shimek, based upon the novel of the same name by [[Louisa May Alcott]].  Maclain Nelson and Stephen Shimek will serve as producers on the film, while Chris Donahue and Marybeth Sprows, will executive produce the film under their Main Dog Productions and Paulist Productions banners, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/lea-thompson-adaptation-little-women-movie-1202078635/|title=Lea Thompson To Star In New Feature Adaptation Of \u2018Little Women\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=April 27, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, Sarah Davenport and [[Ian Bohen]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/ryan-hansen-bum-deal-ian-bohen-little-women-1202107757/|title=Ryan Hansen To Co-Star In \u2018Bum Deal\u2019; Ian Bohen Joins \u2018Little Women\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=June 8, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] began in June 2017, in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/artsliving/2017/04/30/modern-take-on-little-women-to-be-filmed-in-utah/|title=Modern take on \u2018Little Women\u2019 to be filmed in Utah|website=[[The Salt Lake City Tribune]]|first=Sean|last=P. Means|date=April 30, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn June 2018, it was announced Pinnacle Peak and [[Pure Flix Entertainment]] would distribute the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pinnacle-peak-to-release-modern-retelling-of-timeless-family-story-little-women-in-theaters-sept-28-300666702.html|title=Pinnacle Peak to Release Modern Retelling of Timeless Family Story \"Little Women\" In Theaters Sept. 28|website=PR Newswire|date=June 14, 2018|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref> It was released in the United States on September 28, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/reelfaith/2018/06/trailer-first-look-at-modern-retelling-of-little-women-starring-lea-thompson.html|title=TRAILER: First Look at Modern Retelling of \u2018Little Women\u2019 Starring Lea Thompson|website=Patheos|first=Dewayne|last=Hamby|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Little Women'' was released alongside ''[[Smallfoot (film)|Smallfoot]]'', ''[[Night School (2018 film)|Night School]]'' and ''[[Hell Fest]]'', and was projected to gross $3\u20135 million from 643 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/night-school-box-office-debut-kevin-hart-tiffany-haddish-1202931274/|title=Kevin Hart-Tiffany Haddish\u2019s \u2018Night School\u2019 to Score High Marks in Box Office Debut|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=September 9, 2018|accessdate=September 25, 2018}}</ref> It ended up grossing just $747,000, finishing 16th at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/night-school-tiffany-haddish-kevin-hart-weekend-box-office-1202472883/|title=\u2018Night School\u2019 Top Of The Weekend\u2019s Box Office Class With $28M; Best Opening For A Comedy So Far This Year|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=September 30, 2018 |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nAccording to the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], 27% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 26 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 4.81/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"This updated version of ''Little Women'' may hold some appeal for newcomers, but fans of the classic source material have far better adaptations to choose from.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/little_women_2018 |title=Little Women (2018) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 40 out of 100 based on 11 critic reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/little-women-2018 |title=Little Women (2018) Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 27, 2018}}</ref> Nell Minow of RogerEbert.com gave it 3 out of 4 stars and wrote, \"For devotees, the essence of the Little Women story remains, and, for newcomers, it is a sweet film that should inspire them to explore the book and the more traditional adaptations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/little-women-2018|title=Little Women Movie Review & Film Summary (2018) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Minow|first=Nell|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> But Elizabeth Weitzman of The Wrap gave it low marks, writing, \"The girls in this contemporary retelling ... are not messy and complex human beings but Hallmark Channel characters, two-dimensional symbols of virtuous nostalgia.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/little-women-film-review-2018-lea-thompson/|title='Little Women' Film Review: Contemporary Take on Literary Classic Feels More Old-Fashioned Than the Original|date=2018-09-27|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Faith-based reviewers were more generous. Kristin Smith of Plugged In said the film \"illustrates the importance of loving one another, of practicing forgiveness and of moving forward despite difficult times.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pluggedin.com/|title=Plugged In|website=Plugged In|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref> Michael Foust of Crosswalk wrote that \"unlike other modern-day film adaptations that spoiled a classic, Little Women is an updated version that doesn\u2019t ruin what made the original great. ...  Here\u2019s hoping [Niederpruem] makes many more like this one.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crosswalk.com/culture/features/5-reasons-you-should-watch-the-newest-little-women.html|title=5 Reasons You Should Watch the Newest Little Women|website=Crosswalk.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB title|6495094}}\n\n{{Little Women}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about sisters]]\n[[Category:Little Women films]]\n[[Category:2018 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Rfl0216", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Women_(2018_film)"}
{"title_page": "Newman Centers", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Organizations|date=April 2015}}\n{{COI|date=September 2012}}\n{{primary sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=September 2012}}\n}}\n\n[[File:St-Philip-Neri-Newman-Center-Tulsa.jpg|thumb|St. Philip Neri Newman Center Tulsa]]\n\n'''Newman Centers''', '''Newman Houses''', '''Newman Clubs''', or '''Newman Communities''' are [[Catholic campus ministry]] centers at secular universities.  The movement was inspired by the writings of Cardinal [[Saint John Henry Newman]] encouraging societies for Catholic students attending secular universities.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090301223919/http://wsunewmancenter.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid=53 \"A Brief History\"]</ref>\n\nThese centers may include residential living space or may be actual houses close to the campus with or without a chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umassdcatholics.com/|title=Home Page - UMass Dartmouth Catholic Campus Mnistry|first=UMass Dartmouth Catholic Campus|last=Mnistry|website=www.umassdcatholics.com}}</ref> Activities vary between centers but usually include both spiritual worship like Sunday mass and [[eucharistic adoration]], social get-togethers (like movies or coffee socials), and group outings (like apple picking, [[March for Life]] events, and amusement parks).\n\n==History==\nThe first Newman club was established at Oxford University by [[Hartwell de la Garde Grissell]] in 1878 as [[Oxford University Catholic Club]], which was renamed in 1888 the Oxford University Newman Society.\n\nThe \u201cNewman Movement\u201d in the United States began in 1883 at the University of Wisconsin when Catholic students joined to form the Melvin Club, names after their hosts, Mr. and Mrs. John C. Melvin.<ref name=naab>Naab, Kathleen.[https://zenit.org/articles/what-newman-centers-owe-their-namesake-part-1/ \"What Newman Centers Owe Their Namesake\", ''Zenit'', August 30, 2010]</ref> The first Newman Club in America was established in 1893 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] by Timothy Harrington,<ref>John Whitney Evans, ''Making the Best of a Bad Job? Newman Chaplains between the Code and the Council'', U.S. Catholic Historian, Vol. 11, No. 1, Sulpicians and Seminaries, Prelates and Priests (Winter, 1993), pp. 35\u201350.</ref> a graduate medical student and former member of the Wisconsin group, together with John Gilbride, James and Joseph Walsh with assistance of Father P. J. Garvey, pastor of the local St. James Catholic Church. The club provided social activities, discussions on the faith, and mutual support for Catholic students in a sometimes hostile academic environment. The meetings were occasions to experience Catholic culture in a secular environment.<ref name=naab/>\n\n[[Cornell]] had one of the first Newman Clubs, organized in 1888. The Newman Club eventually became a full-fledged campus parish, the [[Cornell Catholic Community]].\n\nIn the early 1900s, the majority of Catholic college students attended private Catholic institutions.{{cn|date=April 2020}} However, over time, a growing number of Catholics began attending secular universities. Initially, small chapels were opened near the campuses of the secular universities.  In 1908, the Catholic clubs began an association which became the [[National Newman Club Federation]]. After [[Vatican II]], the U.S. bishops placed the \"Newman Apostolate\" under the care of the [[Catholic Campus Ministry Association]].<ref>Long-Garcia, [https://www.uscatholic.org/life/2012/01/newman-centers-brief-history \"Newman Centers: A brief history\", ''U.S.Catholic'', (Vol. 77, No. 2).February 2012, pp. 27-31]</ref>\n\nAccording to The Newman Connection <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmanconnection.com/|title=Home|website=The Newman Connection}}</ref>, a US [[Catholic Church]] Campus Ministries non-profit organization, there are over 2,000 Newman Centers in the United States.  \n\n==Ministry and services==\nThe centers provide pastoral services and ministries to their Catholic communities, in particular to the Roman Catholic student population within the universities. However, since these centers are located on university campuses, those of other [[Christian denomination]]s often come and participate as well. A variety of university and parish related meetings and social events take place at the centers, as well as personal events including [[Marriage in the Catholic Church|Catholic weddings]], anniversary celebrations, [[Baptism#Roman_Catholicism|baptisms]], [[Mass in the Catholic Church|masses]] and funeral receptions.\n\n==United States==\nHere are a few examples of campuses with Newman Centers:\n\n[[File:St. John&#039;s Catholic Newman Center Champaign, Illinois.jpg|thumb|St. John&#039;s Catholic Newman Center Champaign, Illinois]]\n[[St. John's Catholic Newman Center]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\u2014formerly known as the Newman Foundation\u2014is the largest in the nation and has been considered one of the model Newman Centers in the United States.{{by whom?|date=April 2020}} The center encompasses three main entities: St. John's Catholic Chapel, Newman Hall, and the Institute of Catholic Thought. It is one of the few Newman Centers that also encompasses a large undergraduate residence, Newman Hall, through the University's Certified Private Housing program, having over 600 live-in residents, a cafeteria, and other services.<ref>[https://www.sjcnc.org/ St. John's Catholic Newman Center]</ref>\n\nThe Newman Center at [[Troy University]] in Troy, Alabama is a coed residence hall which opened in 2013.  The Newman Halls will house 376 residents, 6 resident assistants, and one live-in married couple who acts as the community directors.<ref>[https://www.troy.edu/student-life-resources/housing/newman-center.html \"Newman Center\", Troy University, Alabama]</ref> \n\nBlessed Pope John Paul II Newman Center at the [[University of Illinois, Chicago]] serves the largest Catholic student population in the Midwest and one of the largest in the country. UIC has 25,000+ students, of which over 15,000 are Catholic. The John Paul II Newman Center in 1999 established the Arthur J. Schmitt Chair in Catholic studies for students to study the Catholic faith and receive college credit for doing so. Currently, students may receive a minor in Catholic studies. Of the other programs the John Paul II Newman Center offers, Vocation Discernment averages 10\u201315 students each year who study to become priests and [[Religious (Catholic)|religious]] brothers and sisters. The Integritas Institute for Ethics, a third program, teaches ethics and morality. The John Paul II Newman Center is in the Catholic [[Archdiocese of Chicago]].<ref>http://www.jp2newman.org </ref>\n\nSt. Mary's Catholic Center at [[Texas A&M University]] decided to turn their permanent parishioners into volunteers for the campus ministry and discontinued all other parish programs not related directly to campus ministry. Two hundred families stayed and the rest went to the other parish in College Station. The Catholic Campus Ministry Association has done presentations before national audiences concerning the success of St. Mary's.\n\n==Canada==\n[[Image:NewmanCentreWestSide.JPG|right|thumb|Toronto's Newman Centre west side]]\n\n[[Newman Centre, Toronto]] is housed in the historical W.D. Matthews House and is under the direction of the [[Archdiocese of Toronto]] and is associated with the neighbouring [[St. Thomas Aquinas Church, Toronto|St. Thomas Aquinas Church]].\n\nThe Newman Centre in Montreal, which serves McGill University and the Archdiocese of Montreal goes back to the Columbian Club (est. 1897) and the Newman Club (est. in 1929).<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNally|first1=Peter|title=History of McGill Newman Centre|url=http://www.newmancentre.org/about.history.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423141135/http://www.newmancentre.org/about.history.shtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 April 2013|website=www.newmancentre.org|publisher=Newman Association Inc. / Catholic Times|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> In 1941, the [[Gerald Emmett Carter|Rev. Gerald Emmett Carter]] (later Cardinal Archbishop of Toronto) was appointed director. In 1949, under his leadership, the Club acquired a new home, \"Newman House,\" located centrally on McGill College Avenue, one block south of the [[Roddick Gates]]. In 1951, the Newman Association of Montreal was created (incorporated under the Bighops' Act). The Association's purpose would be to support the Catholic community at McGill University. In 1954 the Newman Association purchased the La Fleur mansion located at 3484 Peel Street, which remains the Centre's Montreal address to this day.<ref>http://cac.mcgill.ca/maxwells/details.php?recordCount=165&Page=11&id=477&pn=&cn=All&pr=All&ct=All&str=&mj=All&mn=All&sta=Built</ref> In 1998 the Newman Institute of Catholic Studies was established under the direction of Dr. Daniel Cere. The Newman Institute of Catholic Studies was federally incorporated in 2000, when the Catholic Studies Minor Concentration was established at McGill University, along with the Kennedy Smith Chair in Catholic Studies.\n\n==Australia==\n[[University of Queensland]] and [[Charles Sturt University]] both house Newman Centres.\n\n==New Zealand==\nA Newman Society, on the lines of the one at Oxford University, was first set up at the [[New Zealand University]] in 1909.<ref>{{Cite Catholic Encyclopedia|wstitle=New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Catholic Youth Ministry}}\n{{Catholic laity}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Catholic organizations established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:University and college residential buildings]]\n[[Category:Catholic youth organizations]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Organizations|date=April 2015}}\n{{COI|date=September 2012}}\n{{primary sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2012}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=September 2012}}\n}}\n\n[[File:St-Philip-Neri-Newman-Center-Tulsa.jpg|thumb|St. Philip Neri Newman Center Tulsa]]\n\n'''Newman Centers''', '''Newman Houses''', '''Newman Clubs''', or '''Newman Communities''' are [[Catholic campus ministry]] centers at secular universities.  The movement was inspired by the writings of Cardinal [[Saint John Henry Newman]] encouraging societies for Catholic students attending secular universities.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090301223919/http://wsunewmancenter.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=29&Itemid=53 \"A Brief History\"]</ref>\n\nThese centers may include residential living space or may be actual houses close to the campus with or without a chapel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umassdcatholics.com/|title=Home Page - UMass Dartmouth Catholic Campus Mnistry|first=UMass Dartmouth Catholic Campus|last=Mnistry|website=www.umassdcatholics.com}}</ref> Activities vary between centers but usually include both spiritual worship like Sunday mass and [[eucharistic adoration]], social get-togethers (like movies or coffee socials), and group outings (like apple picking, [[March for Life]] events, and amusement parks).\n\n==History==\nThe first Newman club was established at at Oxford University by [[Hartwell de la Garde Grissell]] in 1878 as [[Oxford University Catholic Club]], which was renamed in 1888 the Oxford University Newman Society.\n\nThe \u201cNewman Movement\u201d in the United States began in 1883 at the University of Wisconsin when Catholic students joined to form the Melvin Club, names after their hosts, Mr. and Mrs. John C. Melvin.<ref name=naab>Naab, Kathleen.[https://zenit.org/articles/what-newman-centers-owe-their-namesake-part-1/ \"What Newman Centers Owe Their Namesake\", ''Zenit'', August 30, 2010]</ref> The first Newman Club in America was established in 1893 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] by Timothy Harrington,<ref>John Whitney Evans, ''Making the Best of a Bad Job? Newman Chaplains between the Code and the Council'', U.S. Catholic Historian, Vol. 11, No. 1, Sulpicians and Seminaries, Prelates and Priests (Winter, 1993), pp. 35\u201350.</ref> a graduate medical student and former member of the Wisconsin group, together with John Gilbride, James and Joseph Walsh with assistance of Father P. J. Garvey, pastor of the local St. James Catholic Church. The club provided social activities, discussions on the faith, and mutual support for Catholic students in a sometimes hostile academic environment. The meetings were occasions to experience Catholic culture in a secular environment.<ref name=naab/>\n\n[[Cornell]] had one of the first Newman Clubs, organized in 1888. The Newman Club eventually became a full-fledged campus parish, the [[Cornell Catholic Community]].\n\nIn the early 1900s, the majority of Catholic college students attended private Catholic institutions.{{cn|date=April 2020}} However, over time, a growing number of Catholics began attending secular universities. Initially, small chapels were opened near the campuses of the secular universities.  In 1908, the Catholic clubs began an association which became the [[National Newman Club Federation]]. After [[Vatican II]], the U.S. bishops placed the \"Newman Apostolate\" under the care of the [[Catholic Campus Ministry Association]].<ref>Long-Garcia, [https://www.uscatholic.org/life/2012/01/newman-centers-brief-history \"Newman Centers: A brief history\", ''U.S.Catholic'', (Vol. 77, No. 2).February 2012, pp. 27-31]</ref>\n\nAccording to The Newman Connection <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newmanconnection.com/|title=Home|website=The Newman Connection}}</ref>, a US [[Catholic Church]] Campus Ministries non-profit organization, there are over 2,000 Newman Centers in the United States.  \n\n==Ministry and services==\nThe centers provide pastoral services and ministries to their Catholic communities, in particular to the Roman Catholic student population within the universities. However, since these centers are located on university campuses, those of other [[Christian denomination]]s often come and participate as well. A variety of university and parish related meetings and social events take place at the centers, as well as personal events including [[Marriage in the Catholic Church|Catholic weddings]], anniversary celebrations, [[Baptism#Roman_Catholicism|baptisms]], [[Mass in the Catholic Church|masses]] and funeral receptions.\n\n==United States==\nHere are a few examples of campuses with Newman Centers:\n\n[[File:St. John&#039;s Catholic Newman Center Champaign, Illinois.jpg|thumb|St. John&#039;s Catholic Newman Center Champaign, Illinois]]\n[[St. John's Catholic Newman Center]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\u2014formerly known as the Newman Foundation\u2014is the largest in the nation and has been considered one of the model Newman Centers in the United States.{{by whom?|date=April 2020}} The center encompasses three main entities: St. John's Catholic Chapel, Newman Hall, and the Institute of Catholic Thought. It is one of the few Newman Centers that also encompasses a large undergraduate residence, Newman Hall, through the University's Certified Private Housing program, having over 600 live-in residents, a cafeteria, and other services.<ref>[https://www.sjcnc.org/ St. John's Catholic Newman Center]</ref>\n\nThe Newman Center at [[Troy University]] in Troy, Alabama is a coed residence hall which opened in 2013.  The Newman Halls will house 376 residents, 6 resident assistants, and one live-in married couple who acts as the community directors.<ref>[https://www.troy.edu/student-life-resources/housing/newman-center.html \"Newman Center\", Troy University, Alabama]</ref> \n\nBlessed Pope John Paul II Newman Center at the [[University of Illinois, Chicago]] serves the largest Catholic student population in the Midwest and one of the largest in the country. UIC has 25,000+ students, of which over 15,000 are Catholic. The John Paul II Newman Center in 1999 established the Arthur J. Schmitt Chair in Catholic studies for students to study the Catholic faith and receive college credit for doing so. Currently, students may receive a minor in Catholic studies. Of the other programs the John Paul II Newman Center offers, Vocation Discernment averages 10\u201315 students each year who study to become priests and [[Religious (Catholic)|religious]] brothers and sisters. The Integritas Institute for Ethics, a third program, teaches ethics and morality. The John Paul II Newman Center is in the Catholic [[Archdiocese of Chicago]].<ref>http://www.jp2newman.org </ref>\n\nSt. Mary's Catholic Center at [[Texas A&M University]] decided to turn their permanent parishioners into volunteers for the campus ministry and discontinued all other parish programs not related directly to campus ministry. Two hundred families stayed and the rest went to the other parish in College Station. The Catholic Campus Ministry Association has done presentations before national audiences concerning the success of St. Mary's.\n\n==Canada==\n[[Image:NewmanCentreWestSide.JPG|right|thumb|Toronto's Newman Centre west side]]\n\n[[Newman Centre, Toronto]] is housed in the historical W.D. Matthews House and is under the direction of the [[Archdiocese of Toronto]] and is associated with the neighbouring [[St. Thomas Aquinas Church, Toronto|St. Thomas Aquinas Church]].\n\nThe Newman Centre in Montreal, which serves McGill University and the Archdiocese of Montreal goes back to the Columbian Club (est. 1897) and the Newman Club (est. in 1929).<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNally|first1=Peter|title=History of McGill Newman Centre|url=http://www.newmancentre.org/about.history.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423141135/http://www.newmancentre.org/about.history.shtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 April 2013|website=www.newmancentre.org|publisher=Newman Association Inc. / Catholic Times|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> In 1941, the [[Gerald Emmett Carter|Rev. Gerald Emmett Carter]] (later Cardinal Archbishop of Toronto) was appointed director. In 1949, under his leadership, the Club acquired a new home, \"Newman House,\" located centrally on McGill College Avenue, one block south of the [[Roddick Gates]]. In 1951, the Newman Association of Montreal was created (incorporated under the Bighops' Act). The Association's purpose would be to support the Catholic community at McGill University. In 1954 the Newman Association purchased the La Fleur mansion located at 3484 Peel Street, which remains the Centre's Montreal address to this day.<ref>http://cac.mcgill.ca/maxwells/details.php?recordCount=165&Page=11&id=477&pn=&cn=All&pr=All&ct=All&str=&mj=All&mn=All&sta=Built</ref> In 1998 the Newman Institute of Catholic Studies was established under the direction of Dr. Daniel Cere. The Newman Institute of Catholic Studies was federally incorporated in 2000, when the Catholic Studies Minor Concentration was established at McGill University, along with the Kennedy Smith Chair in Catholic Studies.\n\n==Australia==\n[[University of Queensland]] and [[Charles Sturt University]] both house Newman Centres.\n\n==New Zealand==\nA Newman Society, on the lines of the one at Oxford University, was first set up at the [[New Zealand University]] in 1909.<ref>{{Cite Catholic Encyclopedia|wstitle=New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Catholic Youth Ministry}}\n{{Catholic laity}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Catholic organizations established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:University and college residential buildings]]\n[[Category:Catholic youth organizations]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": 